<TEXT>
the courting couple in richard greenbergs the 
american plan resembled wounded butterflies and the audience was 
left longing for their escape from the wicked widow who aims so 
well with her butterfly net 
the american plan directed by evan yionoulis opened sunday 
at the manhattan theater club and was to run through jan 18 
wendy makkena plays the fey 20ish lili adler who says things 
that indicate shes unbalanced dw moffett in the role of nick 
lockridge is the visitor to a catskills hotel across the lake who 
woos her 
lilis widowed mother played with a sophisticated turn by joan 
copeland with a german accent is determined to keep lili to 
herself though why is never made clear 
she tells nick that lili isnt just charmingly neurotic but has 
been in a mental hospital 
greenberg best known here for his play eastern standard 
drops in undefined mysteries and undercurrents to give the audience 
little chills 
the audience quickly sided with nick and lili hoping they can 
get together even if he seems to be a fortunehunter 
when the widow fails to warn nick off she tells him shell send 
him to college after the marriage she repeats those words in front 
of lili knowing it will send her into a minibreakdown and help 
her to isolate her daughter 
so that the audience doesnt think its attending a rewrite of 
the heiress greenberg has an old love of nicks show up and 
its a man 
the final scene is played in the adler apartment in 1970 10 
years after the catskills scenes 
the plot suffers somewhat lili says things that dont tally 
with what went before also her personality is markedly changed 
brittle and downtoearth sane makkena seemed uncomfortable with 
the new persona and presented it rather weakly 
how the story ends is less interesting than the personalities of 
the three main characters and the hints of frightening unknowns in 
their backgrounds and lives 
