<TEXT>
a kgb official speaking at a moscow factory 
last year was asked why mikhail gorbachev was surrounded by two 
rows of worriedlooking guys trying to look in all directions 
his answer according to soviet news reports was that there 
is terrorism and there are all kinds of psychological disorders 
resulting from constant stress 
the kremlin in other words is getting a taste of its own 
medicine 
after supporting international terrorism for decades to 
destabilize the united states and its allies the soviet leadership 
is being confronted with a growing wave of terrorist activity from 
within us counterterrorism experts say 
the same political relaxation that has given birth to 
unprecedented democratic reforms in the 15 soviet republics also 
has lifted the lid on longrepressed aspirations and grievances 
the result has been a general breakdown of law and order 
ranging from new yorkstyle muggings to sophisticated political 
terrorism 
the terrorists run the gamut from nationalists seeking 
independence for their republics to groups distressed by worsening 
economic shortages to individuals unable to cope with the rapid 
changes in soviet society 
the kgb the countrys internal security agency is taking the 
lead in handling the threat but the problem is bedeviling 
gorbachev and the central leadership and theyre hard pressed to 
respond said dick combs a staff member of the senate armed 
services committee who studies the political implications of 
terrorism 
intelligence files made available by the new governments of 
eastern europe are confirming longheld suspicions of western 
counterterrorism officials the sovietled communist bloc 
supported and in some cases sponsored palestinian european and 
south american terrorism 
for example the communist government of east germany knew of 
plans by libyanbacked agents to bomb a discotheque in west berlin 
four years ago according to dennis pluchinsky of the state 
departments bureau of diplomatic security the 1986 attack killed 
one american serviceman and led to a us bombing raid on libya 
but now that the threat has turned against them soviet leaders 
have been eager to cooperate with the west in countering 
international terrorism american officials say 
and they also have asked for help to combat their domestic 
threat said one official western agencies however have turned 
them down citing reluctance to entangle themselves with domestic 
soviet strife said the official who spoke only on condition of 
anonymity 
the list of incidents is long it is made more startling by the 
new openness of the media which as recently as last year was 
banned from publishing any news of attacks on authorities 
in the caucasus nationalists blew up railroad cars and tracks 
several times last summer for two years running the may day 
ceremonies in moscow have been disrupted by political malcontents 
throwing firebombs the soviet airline aeroflot suffered 13 
hijackings or attempted hijackings last summer and has received 
more than 100 bomb threats this year 
yuri plekhanov head of the kgb unit that protects gorbachev 
said recently that every month his agents arrest more than 10 
citizens with criminal intentions 
the head of the kgb in the ukraine nm golushko said recently 
that one cannot ignore the real danger of nuclear terrorism 
attacks on nuclear plants and crimes committed using radioactive 
material 
although counterterrorism measures have been introduced they 
have been impeded by the governments progressively enfeebled grip 
on society said gabriel schoenfeld a senior fellow at the 
center for strategic and international studies in washington 
schoenfeld an expert on internal soviet affairs said attempts 
to control the threat have been further hampered by backward 
technology and shortage of everything from walkietalkies to metal 
detectors 
for example the police need 900000 batteries every year yet 
central planners in moscow have promised only 150000 for 1990 he 
said 
for the time being the terrorist threat may be checked by the 
very flaws that created it 
the unreliable telephone and travel network presents 
difficulties for planners of terrorist incidents so do the strict 
controls still in place on internal travel and the lowtechnology 
weaponry available on the black market 
but further liberalization could benefit terrorists schoenfeld 
said 
in the meantime soviet officials are coming clean about past 
support for terrorists said the state departments pluchinsky 
they have said for example that the notorious marxist radical 
known as carlos who terrorized europe in the 1970s in the pay of 
palestinian groups was granted asylum in communist hungary 
