<TEXT>
a double standard encouraged by international 
agreements exists for foreign airlines operating in the united 
states endangering passengers crews and people on the ground a 
newspaper reported sunday 
the federal aviation administration never verifies the 
qualifications of pilots for foreign airlines and fails to inspect 
foreignowned airline equipment unless the other government 
requests it according to new york newsday 
in its fivemonth investigation newsday ran a computer analysis 
of some 700 accidents worldwide conducted scores of interviews 
and reviewed thousands of documents some obtained through the 
freedom of information act 
newsday said pilots for some foreign carriers dont get training 
in such basic elements as supervising crews and using devices that 
warn of collision with high terrain 
in the last 20 years almost 21000 people have been killed on 
foreign airlines those carriers make about half of all flights but 
account for 80 percent of the deaths worldwide newsday said 
this year the gap was even wider almost 500 people died on 
foreign planes while only 37 were killed on us carriers 
the statistics exclude accidents caused by sabotage or 
terrorism 
faa spokesman fred ferrar in washington said sunday he hadnt 
seen the story and didnt want to comment 
