<TEXT>
environmental protection agency officials 
say theyre stumped by the disappearance of pcbs from a hazardous 
waste site that once had high concentrations of the cancercausing 
substance 
polychlorinated biphenyls once used as insulators in electrical 
transformers were banned by the federal government in the 1970s 
they have not been known to break down in the environment and have 
been considered nearly impossible to destroy 
but officials say a lagoon at the former camor oil rerefinery 
site which once contained more than triple the concentration of 
pcbs allowed by law now appears free of the contaminants 
epa spokeswoman sue pastor said agency officials are studying 
the site to find out what happened 
the epa cited camor in january 1985 for pcbs in three of 11 
waste oil lagoons the company filed for bankruptcy two years 
later 
jack barnette an epa supervisor for emergency response helped 
oversee a containment and temporary cleanup project in which crews 
combined the three infested lagoons drained and treated the 
wastewater and added lime to help harden the waste 
the epa then covered the new lagoon with a tarp to prevent rain 
from washing contaminants out of it 
when epa officials returned to test the lagoon in mid1988 they 
found the oil sludge intact but the pcbs gone barnette said 
well water monitoring around the site shows the chemicals did 
not seep out of the lagoon he said officials say the pcbs appear 
to have disintegrated into harmless chemical components 
barnette said the leading theory is that high heat and low 
moisture during a long drought in 1988 combined to disintegrate the 
contaminants 
lime used to harden the sludge may have also helped break down 
the pcbs but so far there is no scientific evidence to prove it 
barnette said 
at a similar site in toledo ohio where the epa began a cleanup 
effort just after the one at camor lime was used to harden sludge 
and the pcbs also disappeared 
we are not sure if it was the environment or the lime or the 
combination but from now on well be using lime when we deal with 
pcbs he said 
